style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>What
is soft tissue contusion</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Soft tissue contusion -
a closed mechanical damage to the&nbsp;soft&nbsp;tissues without apparent
violation of their anatomical integrity&nbsp;-&nbsp;STI.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>The
disease is also known as</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>In English, the disease
is called Soft Tissue Contusion.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Causes</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Soft tissue injuries
occur only as a result of direct mechanical action.&nbsp;They can be obtained
by falling, hit with a blunt object, squeezing, domestic and industrial
injuries.&nbsp;Injury with soft tissue injury (without violating the integrity
of the skin) can cause rupture of blood vessels of the skin, subcutaneous fat
layer, collagen fibers and individual fat lobules.&nbsp;Sometimes, with a
bruise, the&nbsp;<b>subcutaneous fat is&nbsp;</b>separated from the
underlying&nbsp;<b>fascia&nbsp;</b>(membrane) of the muscles;&nbsp;less often,
there is a simultaneous damage to the fascia itself and the
muscle.&nbsp;The&nbsp;<b>periosteum&nbsp;</b>may be damaged&nbsp;.&nbsp;The
severity of soft tissue injury is determined both by the strength of the impact
and the condition of the tissues to which it
fell.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Who is at risk</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;
color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Children (active games);</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>athletes;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>engaged in hard physical labor.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>How
often does it occur</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>This is the most common
traumatic injury.&nbsp;Bruises vstre&nbsp;-&nbsp;chayut both independently and
accompanied by other, more severe herbs&nbsp;-&nbsp;mothers (sprains,
fractures, damage to internal organs), are one of the components of
polytrauma.&nbsp;Most often subjected to bruise the skin and subcutaneous
tissue, but possible and bruised vnut&nbsp;-&nbsp;nal organs (brain, heart,
lungs).</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span style='font-size:18.0pt;
font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Symptoms</span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>Hemorrhages - from small (punctate) to large limited blood
accumulations (bruising,&nbsp;<b>hematoma&nbsp;</b>);&nbsp;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:-.25in;line-height:
normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:Symbol;color:black'>·<span
style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>soreness and swelling of the injury site;</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-bottom:14.0pt;margin-left:64.9pt;text-indent:
-.25in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:
Symbol;color:black'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>partial limitation of the mobility of body parts (with extensive
bruises).</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><b><span lang=EN-US
style='font-size:18.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Diagnosis
